            <p>Melvin G. Winstock Esq<lb/></p>
            <p>My Dear Sir<lb/></p>
            <p>I have just received your note.  I hasten<lb/> to acknowledge it&#44; and express my sentiments with<lb/> the openness usual with me.<lb/></p>
            <p>A short time ago Mr Oscar Teller asked that I would<lb/> state when I <del>considered</del> thought it suitable to hold a meeting<lb/> in the interest of the projected &#34;Publication Society&#34;.  I<lb/> answered that I would be on hand whenever held.<lb/>  Yesterday I read <del>in full</del> the whole lecture on &#34;the Saturday and<lb/> the Sunday Sabbath.......by Rabbi Joseph Braus&#45;<lb/>kopf DD&#34;.  The <del>grief</del> pain it caused me was profound great<lb/></p>
            <p>It were idle to discuss its contents in a letter&#44; but to<lb/> one whole <del>whole</del> life&#45;work has been an endeavour to<lb/> strengthen Judaism as received and as suffered for&#44; trying<lb/> to awaken a sense of reverence for it in all classes of<lb/> our people&#44; without breathing a word of contempt for<lb/> fellow creatures of another creed&#44; that &#34;Sunday lecture of<lb/> April 2 AM 1888&#34;&#44; must have <del>given a shock</del> proved a source of deep regret.<lb/></p>
            <p>I have been anxiously watched Dr Krauskopf&#39;s<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="2"/>
            <p>course from its beginning&#44; and I could not help seeing<lb/> that it was destructive of all which I hold dear.<lb/>  Still&#44; the closing sermon of the season <del>furied</del> shocked me irre&#45;<lb/>pressibly.  Among other things of which the preacher<lb/> makes public boast&#44; is the following&#58; &#34;The American<lb/> Jewish Publication Society&#44; about to be organized in<lb/> this city&#44; has emanated from the Sunday Service.&#34;<lb/>  God forbid that I shall sit in council to legislate<lb/> concerning a scheme that has so unjewish an origin.<lb/>  I will not &#34;be a member of the committee of ar&#45;<lb/>rangements&#34;.  I <del>regret lament</del> regret it&#44; because the opponents<lb/> of my religion&#45;&#45;Alas&#33; men born in it&#33;&#45;&#45;will mis&#45;<lb/>construe my declination.  Suffice <del>for me to</del> that I<lb/> know <del>that I hear no ill will against me&#44;</del> to be free from the sin of hatred&#44; and<lb/> as for jealousy&#44; I can have none.  My career is<lb/> <del>pretty well</del> nearly run.  I cannot expect at my age to<lb/> enter the lists with youths&#44; through which I am permitted<lb/> to work &#38; I trust not to out live my capacity for it&#44; I shall defend what I consider true.<lb/>  Yours friendly<lb/> S. Morais<lb/> May 7. 88<lb/></p>
